Q: What is Java?
A: Java is a high-level, object-oriented programming language developed by Sun Microsystems. It is designed to be platform-independent and follows the "Write Once, Run Anywhere" (WORA) principle.

Q: Explain the main features of Java.
A: Key features of Java include:
- Object-oriented
- Platform-independent (via the Java Virtual Machine)
- Simple and easy to learn
- Distributed computing support (via RMI and EJB)
- Multi-threading
- Robust and secure (garbage collection, exception handling, etc.)
- Dynamic and extensible

Q: What is the difference between == and .equals() in Java?
A: == is used for comparing primitive data types or checking if two references point to the same object. .equals() is used for comparing the content or values of objects and is usually overridden in custom classes.

Q: What is the Java Virtual Machine (JVM)?
A: JVM is a virtual machine that enables Java applications to run on any device or operating system. It provides an abstraction layer between the Java program and the underlying hardware and operating system.

Q: What is the difference between an abstract class and an interface?
A: An abstract class can have both abstract and concrete methods, while an interface contains abstract methods (and default/static methods in modern Java). A class can extend only one abstract class but implement multiple interfaces. Abstract classes can have constructors, while interfaces cannot.

Q: Explain the concept of multithreading in Java.
A: Multithreading allows two or more threads to execute concurrently. Java supports multithreading through the Thread class and the Runnable interface.

Q: What is the Java Collections Framework?
A: The Java Collections Framework provides interfaces and classes for storing and manipulating groups of objects. It includes interfaces such as List, Set, and Map, and classes such as ArrayList, HashSet, and HashMap.

Q: What is the difference between String, StringBuilder, and StringBuffer?
A: String is immutable. StringBuilder and StringBuffer are mutable. StringBuilder is faster but not thread-safe, while StringBuffer is thread-safe.

Q: What is the purpose of the finalize() method?
A: The finalize() method is called by the garbage collector before an object is reclaimed. It allows cleanup operations such as releasing resources. (It is deprecated in modern Java.)

Q: Explain the concept of exception handling in Java.
A: Exception handling uses try, catch, and finally blocks. The try block contains code that may throw an exception, the catch block handles the exception, and the finally block executes whether an exception occurs or not.

Q: What is the super keyword used for in Java?
A: The super keyword refers to the parent class. It is used to call superclass methods, access superclass fields, or invoke the superclass constructor.

Q: What is the difference between method overloading and method overriding?
A: Method overloading allows multiple methods with the same name but different parameter lists in the same class. Method overriding allows a subclass to provide its own implementation of a method defined in the superclass.

Q: Explain the static keyword in Java.
A: The static keyword declares members that belong to the class rather than an object. Static members are shared among all instances and can be accessed using the class name.

Q: What is the purpose of the transient keyword in Java?
A: The transient keyword prevents a field from being serialized when an object is serialized. It is commonly used for sensitive or temporary data.

Q: What is the this keyword in Java?
A: The this keyword refers to the current object. It is used to distinguish instance variables from local variables and to invoke constructors or methods of the current class.

Q: Explain the concept of autoboxing and unboxing in Java.
A: Autoboxing is the automatic conversion of a primitive type into its corresponding wrapper class. Unboxing is the automatic conversion of a wrapper object back to its primitive type.

Q: What is the try-with-resources statement in Java?
A: The try-with-resources statement automatically closes resources declared in the try statement after execution, even if an exception occurs. Resources must implement the AutoCloseable interface.

Q: Explain the concept of garbage collection in Java.
A: Garbage collection automatically removes objects that are no longer reachable, freeing memory and preventing memory leaks.

Q: What is the difference between public, private, protected, and default access modifiers in Java?
A: Public members are accessible from anywhere. Private members are accessible only within the same class. Protected members are accessible within the same package and by subclasses. Default members are accessible only within the same package.

Q: Explain the concept of the Java Naming and Directory Interface (JNDI).
A: JNDI is an API that provides naming and directory services. It allows Java applications to locate and access resources such as databases, LDAP services, and enterprise objects.

Q: What is the difference between an interface and an abstract class in Java?
A: An abstract class can have both abstract and concrete methods and can have constructors. An interface defines a contract that classes implement and allows multiple inheritance of type. A class can implement multiple interfaces but extend only one abstract class.

Q: How does Java support multiple inheritance?
A: Java supports multiple inheritance through interfaces. A class can implement multiple interfaces, allowing it to inherit behavior from multiple sources without the ambiguity of multiple class inheritance.

