Q: What is the purpose of the hashCode() and equals() methods in Java?
A: hashCode() returns a hash code value for an object and is used by hash-based collections like HashMap. equals() compares the contents or values of two objects and is often overridden in custom classes.

Q: Explain the concept of the ClassLoader in Java.
A: The ClassLoader is a part of the JVM responsible for loading classes into memory at runtime. It enables dynamic loading of classes, making Java applications flexible and extensible.

Q: What is the purpose of the super() constructor call?
A: The super() constructor call invokes the constructor of the superclass. It must be the first statement in a subclass constructor. If omitted, Java automatically inserts a default super() call.

Q: Explain the StringTokenizer class in Java.
A: StringTokenizer is a legacy class used to split a string into tokens based on specified delimiters. It is simpler but less flexible than the split() method.

Q: What is the purpose of the Package class in Java?
A: The Package class provides information about a package, such as its name, version, implementation title, and vendor details.

Q: Explain the try-with-resources statement introduced in Java 7.
A: The try-with-resources statement automatically closes resources after execution, even if an exception occurs. Resources must implement the AutoCloseable or Closeable interface.

Q: What is the difference between Error and Exception in Java?
A: Error represents serious problems that applications should not normally handle, such as OutOfMemoryError. Exception represents conditions that applications can catch and handle.

Q: Explain the static initialization block in Java.
A: A static initialization block is executed only once when a class is loaded into memory. It is used to initialize static variables or perform one-time setup tasks.

Q: What is the purpose of the break statement in a switch statement?
A: The break statement exits the switch block after a matching case is executed, preventing fall-through to subsequent cases.

Q: Explain the concept of Enum in Java.
A: An Enum is a special data type that represents a fixed set of constants. It provides type safety and makes code more readable.

Q: What is the purpose of the volatile modifier in Java?
A: The volatile modifier ensures that changes made to a variable by one thread are immediately visible to other threads, helping maintain data consistency.

Q: Explain the concept of the finalize() method in the context of garbage collection.
A: The finalize() method is called before an object is garbage collected, allowing it to perform cleanup operations. It is deprecated in modern Java.

Q: How does Java support the implementation of multithreading?
A: Java supports multithreading using the Thread class and the Runnable interface. It also provides synchronization mechanisms such as synchronized methods and blocks.

Q: Explain the concept of the assert keyword in Java.
A: The assert keyword is used for debugging. It checks whether a condition is true and throws an AssertionError if the condition is false.

Q: What is the purpose of the System class in Java?
A: The System class provides access to system resources, including standard input/output streams, system properties, environment variables, and garbage collection methods.

Q: Explain the concept of the java.util.concurrent package in Java.
A: The java.util.concurrent package provides utilities for concurrent programming, including thread pools, locks, concurrent collections, synchronization tools, and executor services.

Q: What is the purpose of the Math class in Java?
A: The Math class provides methods for performing mathematical operations such as square roots, powers, logarithms, trigonometric functions, and random number generation.

Q: Explain the concept of method references in Java 8.
A: Method references provide a shorthand way to refer to methods using the :: operator. They improve code readability and are commonly used with lambda expressions.

Q: What is the try-with-resources statement, and how does it simplify resource management?
A: The try-with-resources statement automatically closes resources declared in the try block, eliminating the need for explicit cleanup code and reducing resource leaks.

Q: Explain the java.nio package and its significance.
A: The java.nio package provides support for non-blocking I/O, buffers, channels, and selectors, enabling faster and more efficient input/output operations.

Q: What is the purpose of the Comparator and Comparable interfaces in Java?
A: Comparable defines the natural ordering of objects using the compareTo() method. Comparator provides custom sorting by implementing the compare() method separately.

Q: Explain the difference between a HashSet and a TreeSet in Java.
A: HashSet stores unique elements without maintaining any order and provides fast access. TreeSet stores unique elements in sorted order using a tree-based data structure.

