Q: How does Java handle memory management, and what is garbage collection?
A: Java uses automatic memory management through garbage collection. The garbage collector identifies and removes objects that are no longer reachable, freeing memory and preventing memory leaks.

Q: What are the differences between String, StringBuffer, and StringBuilder?
A: String is immutable. StringBuffer is mutable and thread-safe but slower. StringBuilder is mutable, not thread-safe, and faster than StringBuffer.

Q: Explain the concept of annotations in Java.
A: Annotations are metadata added to Java code using the @ symbol. They provide information to the compiler, tools, or runtime and are used for documentation, code generation, and configuration.

Q: What is the purpose of the java.util.stream package in Java 8?
A: The java.util.stream package provides streams for processing collections using functional-style operations such as filter, map, reduce, and collect.

Q: Explain the concept of the Observer design pattern in Java.
A: The Observer pattern is a behavioral design pattern in which a subject notifies its registered observers whenever its state changes. It is commonly used for event handling.

Q: What is the super keyword used for in constructors, and when is it required?
A: The super keyword is used to call the constructor of the superclass. It must be the first statement in a subclass constructor when invoking a specific parent constructor.

Q: Explain the concept of inner static classes in Java.
A: Inner static classes are nested classes declared with the static keyword. They do not require an instance of the outer class and can access only the outer class's static members.

Q: What is the purpose of the java.lang package in Java?
A: The java.lang package contains fundamental classes such as Object, String, Math, Thread, and System. It is automatically imported into every Java program.

Q: Explain the javac compiler in Java and how it differs from the java command.
A: The javac command compiles Java source code into bytecode (.class files). The java command executes the compiled bytecode using the JVM.

Q: What is the purpose of the String Pool in Java?
A: The String Pool stores string literals so that identical strings share the same memory location, improving memory efficiency and performance.

Q: Explain the concept of serialization and deserialization in Java.
A: Serialization converts an object into a byte stream for storage or transmission. Deserialization converts the byte stream back into an object.

Q: What is the purpose of the this reference in Java constructors?
A: The this reference refers to the current object. In constructors, it is used to distinguish instance variables from parameters and to call another constructor in the same class.

Q: Explain the concept of the java.lang.Class class in Java.
A: The Class class represents classes and interfaces at runtime. It provides information about constructors, methods, fields, and annotations, and is used in reflection.

Q: What are lambda expressions, and how are they used in Java 8?
A: Lambda expressions provide a concise way to implement functional interfaces using the -> operator. They simplify code and support functional programming.

Q: What is the purpose of the java.util.Collections class in Java?
A: The Collections class provides utility methods for working with collections, including sorting, searching, reversing, shuffling, and synchronizing collections.

Q: Explain the concept of the Object class in Java.
A: The Object class is the root class of the Java class hierarchy. Every Java class directly or indirectly inherits from Object and its methods such as toString(), equals(), and hashCode().

Q: What is the purpose of the java.lang.Runtime class in Java?
A: The Runtime class provides access to the Java runtime environment. It allows applications to execute external programs, access memory information, and interact with the garbage collector.

Q: Explain the concept of the java.lang.ThreadLocal class.
A: ThreadLocal provides thread-specific variables. Each thread has its own independent copy of the variable, making it useful for storing thread-specific data.

Q: What is the purpose of the java.util.Arrays class in Java?
A: The Arrays class provides utility methods for array operations such as sorting, searching, comparing, filling, and converting arrays to strings.

Q: Explain the concept of the java.lang.Exception class hierarchy in Java.
A: The Exception hierarchy includes checked and unchecked exceptions. Checked exceptions must be handled or declared, while unchecked exceptions (RuntimeException) do not require explicit handling.

Q: What is the java.time package, and how does it improve date and time handling in Java?
A: The java.time package, introduced in Java 8, provides a modern API for handling dates, times, durations, and time zones. It is immutable, thread-safe, and more powerful than the older Date and Calendar classes.

Q: Explain the concept of the java.lang.StrictMath class.
A: The StrictMath class provides mathematical functions that produce consistent results across all JVM implementations, ensuring platform-independent calculations.

